Today on Human Rights Day, where this year’s United Nations General Assembly theme is “Dignity, Freedom, and Justice for All,” we honor the survivors of the Tulsa Race Massacre as we visited them this past Wednesday with @business_for_good_ founders  Ed & Lisa Mitzen (@lisamitzen).

For @msttunie, @mslachanze & @vanessawilliamsofficial it was a “humbling, emotional, and inspiring day.”

As members of the Black theatre community, we stand together to help protect Black people, Black theatre, and Black lives of all shapes and orientations in communities across the country. Our voices are united to educate, empower, and inspire through excellence and activism in the pursuit of justice and equality. We will tell our stories, preserve our history, and ensure the legacy of Black theatre as American culture. 

This is one of our stories. This is our history. And we must keep telling it!

The Last Bath…so much to relay and too deep to explain it all. We walked the path of our enslaved ancestors to their last bath while in captivity before they were loaded on the ship to the New World. Two rivers met. They were hastily cleansed in shackles in the still water but in our lifetime we stood in the clear, fresh running river and had the chance to be blessed by the local chief , adorned with herbs of protection, share our gratitude through prayer for all our ancestors who survived the horrific journey to make our lives possible. We took the path of return. Forever grateful to be welcomed back to give thanks 🙏🏽. Ase Ase #assinmanso #ghana

THE STORIES BEHIND MY PHOTOS:
In 1996 when I was asked to photograph 3 time US Olympic #fencer, #sharonmonplaisir I envisioned a #robinhood like scenario.  A modern version of the story, with a black woman of much dignity representing the role in my photograph.  When she and I walked into a dense fern forest behind my house, I looked back at her through my camera and saw the strength that I had only recently imagined.  Sharon Monplaisir has inspired many individuals of humble status with courage, generosity and great respect. #foil #sword #usafencing  #peterwestbrookfoundation #blackhistorymonth

I had the pleasure of being part of a collaboration of Black entrepreneurs who joined forces to honor Black History Month with my first major book signing event in NY held last Sunday (2/26). It was sparked by Gwen Clayton, who expressed interest to host it at Alvin & Friends, which she founded with her husband Alvin 15 years ago in New Rochelle. They are longtime friends, their contemporary Southern and Caribbean cuisine is scrumptious, and their restaurant is adorned with eye-catching artworks by Alvin who is a celebrated artist/painter. Gwen pulled in Otilia Taylor-Tanner to be our book partner. She also lives in New Rochelle, is a member of the American Booksellers Association, and owns her own bespoke virtual imprint, The Humble Bumble Bookseller. Then my dear friend, Harriette Cole, who has authored 7 books, founded Dreamleapers, an educational platform that helps people access and activate their dreams, among many her many other talents and illustrious career agreed to share/host an Author Conversation with me. And Astro Raw, ( Lucas Goodman) partner with my daughter Jillian in Lion Babe and father of my adorable grandson Sunny ☀️ did a DJ set. I was emotionally touched by the way my family and friends showered me with their warmth and generosity of spirit throughout the evening. lSpecial thanks to Gwen, Alvin, Harriette, Otilia and her daughter Psalm, Lucas, and all my friends and family who took the time to attend and purchase my book. It was a very special night that I will remember and forever cherish fondly Also, thanks to George Chinsee (Harriette’s husband) a noted photographer who took the lovely image featured in this post.

As a proud member of the @roundaboutnyc board for over 10 years , our beloved  Creator and Artistic Director #ToddHaimes has passed.  I first worked with Todd on “Sondheim on Sondheim “at Studio 54 as a cast member and shortly thereafter joined the board. Todd was innovative, supportive, collaborative and willing to commit to change as the world of theater continued to evolve.  He recently created the Forward Fund which combines Roundabout’s existing efforts around community partnerships, access, and diversity-focused career development with newly created initiatives to spotlight writers from historically excluded communities. This, along with our five-year strategic plan to center equity, diversity, inclusion, and anti-racism  and partnered with us as @blacktheatreunited 🖤The Education Program has changed so many young lives and is a true testament to Todd’s vision of making theater accessible to everyone. What a loss and what an impact he made. RIP Your leadership will surely be missed

This is my incredible #rescuecrew that came to help my Bestie since 2nd grade at Roaring Brook Elementary School @tonianncallwood in her time of need 🧹 Toni’s dynamic mother , Lula Callwood , suddenly died in her arms at age 91 last Christmas season and left Toni with the responsibility of 4 houses to manage, sort through, try to repair, sell, collect rent, etc… All of which is overwhelming for anyone!  Where do you even begin? Particularly when Lula Callwood was famous in Camden for her avid collecting of antique chairs, china, artwork, clothing, tables, bureaus, lamps, sofas, sculptures and pretty much everything that was unique and beautiful.  My first call was to @ctdesignlv who as a interior designer, event planner and master organizer, would have the plan of attack plus the perfect support we would need to tackle this mission. Christopher brought @cpoe0390 and @ajbell.dwg to SC , ordered dumpsters, bought weed whackers, laid tarps , swept collapsed ceilings , trimmed vines coming through windows, busted doors open and we spent 3 hot, sweaty and exhausting days moving everything in sight!  We couldn’t even clean out any of the 3 out of 4 houses but organized enough to help Toni see the light at the end of the tunnel, leaving her with 2 dumpster full of trash and a Camden community ready to step in and take over where we left off.  True friendship is being there when you don’t even have to ask. Thank you Christopher, Cody , AJ for your unrelenting hard work and true dedication …and Toni we love you and this is for Lula, Lula, Lula 🕊️🥂

So excited to be joining @awonderfulworldbway as lead producing team for the Broadway-aimed “A Wonderful World”, a bio-musical about jazz icon Louis Armstrong starring James Monroe Iglehard.  The full cast for the musical will feature Ta’Rea Campbell (The Lion King, The Book of Mormon) as Lucille Wilson, Jennie Harney-Fleming (The Color Purple, Hamilton) as Lil Hardin, Brennyn Lark (Six, Les Misérables) as Alpha Smith and Khalifa White (Caroline, or Change, Little Shop of Horrors) as Daisy Parker. Following Armstrong’s musical path from New Orleans to Chicago, A Wonderful World will premiere this year at the Saenger Theatre in New Orleans (October 1-8) before moving to the Cadillac Palace Theatre in Chicago (October 11-29). Producers plan to move the show to Broadway, although dates and other details have not been announced.

“I became interested in joining the producing team after I worked with Carl White and Greg Rae on a play I am starring in and co-producing called “One Reach Away,” Williams said in a statement. “They told me about this Louis Armstrong piece, and I had to read it. What captured me was the life of Louis was told through the perspectives of his four wives, and that’s when my producing partner Liz Curtis and I dove in.”

Williams joins producers Thomas E. Rodgers, Jr., Renee Rodgers, Andrew Delaplaine, Liz Curtis, and Martian Entertainment (Carl D. White and Gregory Rae).

The cast of A Wonderful World also features DeWitt Fleming, Jr., Gavin Gregory, Matthew Greenwood and Matt Wolpe, with Ronnie Bowman, Lindsey Corey, Jamal Christopher Douglas, Alexandra Frohlinger, Afra Hines, Alan Kelly, Ashley McManus, Aurelia Michael, Alysha Morgan, Jarran Muse, Aaron Michael Ray, Khadijah Rolle, Dave Schoonover, Brett Sturgis, Renell Taylor and Dori Waymer.

Exciting news! The highly anticipated book “Pamella Roland: Dressing the Spotlight” is on the horizon. Get ready to immerse yourself in the incredible journey that unfolds in the life of Louis Armstrong. With an exceptional cast and creative team, this production promises to leave a profound mark!

It is wonderful, refreshing and exciting to see new pieces being supported and brought to the spotlight! 

“I became interested in joining the producing team after I worked with Carl White and Greg Rae on a play I am starring in and co-producing called One Reach Away,” Williams said in a statement. “They told me about this Louis Armstrong piece, and I had to read it. What captured me was the life of Louis was told through the perspectives of his four wives, and that’s when my producing partner Liz Curtis and I dove in.” [source: @deadline ]

Introducing: A New Home for the World 🌳

Four years ago, we faced the results of a once-in-a-lifetime natural crisis in the aftermath of Hurricane Dorian. 

Destruction and despair ripped through the Bahamas as we bore the brunt of evermore severe and frequent extreme weather events thanks to climate change. 

In the coming years, I met and collaborated with some of the world’s best and brightest minds in a desperate search to avoid future crises and to help build back our community. 

Today, we introduce the first house built in the Bahamas using Partanna technology: the world’s first carbon negative, climate resilient home. 

This is our chance not just to build back but to break the relationship between construction and climate change once and for all. 

This isn’t just a house. It’s a new home for the world.
